  "prompt": "Can we do court marriage in any state?",
  "response": "Yes, in India, you can perform a **court marriage** in any state, irrespective of where you and your partner reside. This is facilitated under the **Special Marriage Act, 1954**, which provides a legal framework for individuals of different religions or those who prefer a civil (non-religious) ceremony to marry without requiring any special permission.\n\n### **Key Features of Court Marriage under the Special Marriage Act:**\n\n1. **Notice of Intended Marriage:**\n   - **Submission:** Both parties must give a written notice to the Marriage Registrar of the district where at least one of the parties has resided for at least **30 days preceding the notice**.\n   - **Publication:** The notice is then published by the Registrar, inviting objections, if any, within **30 days**.\n\n2. **Eligibility Criteria:**\n   - **Age:** The bride must be at least **18 years** old, and the groom must be at least **21 years** old.\n   - **Consent:** Both parties must **consent** to the marriage freely.\n   - **Monogamy:** Neither party should have a spouse living at the time of marriage.\n   - **Mental Capacity:** Both parties should be of **sound mind** and capable of giving consent.\n\n3. **No Religious Ceremonies Required:**\n   - The court marriage is purely a **civil process**, so no religious rites or ceremonies are necessary.\n\n4. **Witnesses:**\n   - **Minimum of three witnesses** is required at the time of the marriage solemnization.\n\n5. **Timeframe:**\n   - If no objections are raised within the 30-day notice period, the marriage can be solemnized on a date decided by the Registrar.\n\n6. **Documents Required:**\n   - **Proof of Age and Residence:** Birth certificates, passport, voter ID, etc.\n   - **Passport-sized Photographs**\n   - **Affidavits:** Both parties may need to sign affidavits declaring their marital status, consent, and other relevant details.\n   - **Previous Marriage Dissolution Documents (if applicable):** Divorce decree, death certificate of former spouse, etc.\n\n### **Benefits of Choosing a Court Marriage:**\n\n- **Simplicity:** The process is straightforward without the need for elaborate ceremonies.\n- **Legal Recognition:** Provides legal recognition to the marriage, making it easier for matters like inheritance, taxation, and property rights.\n- **Uniformity:** Applicable uniformly across India, providing consistency irrespective of the state.\n\n### **Steps to Get Married Through Court Marriage:**\n\n1. **Apply for Notice:**\n   - Submit the notice along with the required documents to the Marriage Registrar.\n\n2. **Publication and Objection Period:**\n   - The Registrar publishes the notice and waits for 30 days to address any objections.\n\n3. **Verification:**\n   - If no valid objections are raised, the Registrar verifies the details and schedules the marriage.\n\n4. **Solemnization:**\n   - The marriage is officially registered in the presence of the Registrar and witnesses.\n\n5. **Marriage Certificate:**\n   - Post-solemnization, a marriage certificate is issued, serving as legal proof of the marriage.\n\n### **Considerations:**\n\n- **Residency:** At least one of the parties must have resided in the state where the marriage is being registered for a minimum of 30 days prior to the application.\n- **Inter-State Marriages:** Since the Special Marriage Act is a central law, it facilitates inter-state marriages seamlessly, ensuring that the marriage is recognized nationwide.\n\n### **Conclusion:**\n\nCourt marriages under the Special Marriage Act, 1954, offer a flexible and legally robust alternative to traditional marriages, especially for couples from different religious backgrounds or those who prefer a secular ceremony. By allowing marriages to be registered in any state, it promotes unity and legal consistency across the country.\n\nIf you're considering a court marriage, it's advisable to consult with the local Marriage Registrar or a legal expert to ensure all requirements are met and to understand any specific procedures that might apply in the state where you intend to get married.",
